# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mbus-metering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] AMR technologies include handheld, mobile and network technologies based on telephony platforms (wired and wireless), radio frequency (RF), or powerline transmission.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] With touch-based AMR, a meter reader carries a handheld computer or data collection device with a wand or probe.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The device automatically collects the readings from a meter by touching or placing the read probe close to a reading coil enclosed in the touchpad.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] When a button is pressed, the probe sends an interrogate signal to the touch module to collect the meter reading.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The software in the device matches the serial number to one in the route database, and saves the meter reading for later download to a billing or data collection computer.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Since the meter reader still has to go to the site of the meter, this is sometimes referred to as "on-site" AMR.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Another form of contact reader uses a standardized infrared port to transmit data.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Protocols are standardized between manufacturers by such documents as ANSI C12.18 or IEC 61107.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] AMR hosting is a back-office solution which allows a user to track their electricity, water, or gas consumption over the Internet.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] All data is collected in near real-time, and is stored in a database by data acquisition software.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The user can view the data via a web application, and can analyze the data using various online analysis tools such as charting load profiles, analyzing tariff components, and verify their utility bill.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Radio frequency based AMR can take many forms.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The more common ones are handheld, mobile, satellite and fixed network solutions.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] There are both two-way RF systems and one-way RF systems in use that use both licensed and unlicensed RF bands.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In a two-way or "wake up" system, a radio signal is normally sent to an AMR meter's unique serial number, instructing its transceiver to power-up and transmit its data.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The meter transceiver and the reading transceiver both send and receive radio signals.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In a one-way "bubble-up" or continuous broadcast type system, the meter transmits continuously and data is sent every few seconds.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This means the reading device can be a receiver only, and the meter a transmitter only.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Data travels only from the meter transmitter to the reading receiver.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] There are also hybrid systems that combine one-way and two-way techniques, using one-way communication for reading and two-way communication for programming functions.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] RF-based meter reading usually eliminates the need for the meter reader to enter the property or home, or to locate and open an underground meter pit.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The utility saves money by increased speed of reading, has less liability from entering private property, and has fewer missed readings from being unable to access the meter.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The technology based on RF is not readily accepted everywhere.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In several Asian countries, the technology faces a barrier of regulations in place pertaining to use of the radio frequency of any radiated power.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] For example, in India the radio frequency which is generally in ISM band is not free to use even for low power radio of 10 mW.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The majority of manufacturers of electricity meters have radio frequency devices in the frequency band of 433/868 MHz for large scale deployment in European countries.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The frequency band of 2.4 GHz can be now used in India for outdoor as well as indoor applications, but few manufacturers have shown products within this frequency band.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Initiatives in radio frequency AMR in such countries are being taken up with regulators wherever the cost of licensing outweighs the benefits of AMR.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In handheld AMR, a meter reader carries a handheld computer with a built-in or attached receiver/transceiver (radio frequency or touch) to collect meter readings from an AMR capable meter.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This is sometimes referred to as "walk-by" meter reading since the meter reader walks by the locations where meters are installed as they go through their meter reading route.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Handheld computers may also be used to manually enter readings without the use of AMR technology as an alternate but this will not support exhaustive data which can be accurately read using the meter reading electronically.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Mobile or "drive-by" meter reading is where a reading device is installed in a vehicle.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The meter reader drives the vehicle while the reading device automatically collects the meter readings.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Often, for mobile meter reading, the reading equipment includes navigational and mapping features provided by GPS and mapping software.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] With mobile meter reading, the reader does not normally have to read the meters in any particular route order, but just drives the service area until all meters are read.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Components often consist of a laptop or proprietary computer, software, RF receiver/transceiver, and external vehicle antennas.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Transmitters for data collection satellites can be installed in the field next to existing meters.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The satellite AMR devices communicate with the meter for readings, and then sends those readings over a fixed or mobile satellite network.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This network requires a clear view to the sky for the satellite transmitter/receiver, but eliminates the need to install fixed towers or send out field technicians, thereby being particularly suited for areas with low geographic meter density.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] There are also meters using AMR with RF technologies such as cellular phone data systems, Zigbee, Bluetooth, Wavenis and others.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Federal Communications Commission (FCC) licensed frequencies and others under FCC Part 15, which allows use of unlicensed radio frequencies.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] WiSmart is a versatile platform which can be used by a variety of electrical home appliances in order to provide wireless TCP/IP communication using the 802.11 b/g protocol.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Devices such as the Smart Thermostat permit a utility to lower a home's power consumption to help manage power demand.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The city of Corpus Christi became one of the first cities in the United States to implement citywide Wi-Fi, which had been free until May 31, 2007, mainly to facilitate AMR after a meter reader was attacked by a dog.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Today many meters are designed to transmit using Wi-Fi, even if a Wi-Fi network is not available, and they are read using a drive-by local Wi-Fi hand held receiver.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The meters installed in Corpus Christi are not directly Wi-Fi enabled, but rather transmit narrow-band burst telemetry on the 460 MHz band.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This narrow-band signal has much greater range than Wi-Fi, so the number of receivers required for the project are far fewer.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Special receiver stations then decode the narrow-band signals and resend the data via Wi-Fi.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Most of the automated utility meters installed in the Corpus Christi area are battery powered.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Wi-Fi technology is unsuitable for long-term battery-powered operation.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] PLC is a method where electronic data is transmitted over power lines back to the substation, then relayed to a central computer in the utility's main office.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This would be considered a type of fixed network system—the network being the distribution network which the utility has built and maintains to deliver electric power.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Such systems are primarily used for electric meter reading.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Some providers have interfaced gas and water meters to feed into a PLC type system.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In 1972, Theodore George "Ted" Paraskevakos, while working with Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system which used digital transmission for security, fire and medical alarm systems as well as meter reading capabilities for all utilities.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This technology was a spin-off of the automatic telephone line identification system, now known as caller ID.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In 1974, Paraskevakos was awarded a U.S. patent for this technology.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In 1977, he launched Metretek, Inc., which developed and produced the first fully automated, commercially available remote meter reading and load management system.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Since this system was developed pre-Internet, Metretek utilized the IBM series 1 mini-computer.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] For this approach, Paraskevakos and Metretek were awarded multiple patents.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The primary driver for the automation of meter reading is not to reduce labor costs, but to obtain data that is difficult to obtain.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] As an example, many water meters are installed in locations that require the utility to schedule an appointment with the homeowner in order to obtain access to the meter.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In many areas, consumers have demanded that their monthly water bill be based on an actual reading, instead of (for example) an estimated monthly usage based on just one actual meter reading made every 12 months.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Early AMR systems often consisted of walk-by and drive-by AMR for residential customers, and telephone-based AMR for commercial or industrial customers.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] What was once a need for monthly data became a need for daily and even hourly readings of the meters.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Consequently, the sales of drive-by and telephone AMR has declined in the US, while sales of fixed networks has increased.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The trend now is to consider the use of advanced meters as part of an advanced metering infrastructure.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Originally AMR devices just collected meter readings electronically and matched them with accounts.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] As technology has advanced, additional data could then be captured, stored, and transmitted to the main computer, and often the metering devices could be controlled remotely.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This can include events alarms such as tamper, leak detection, low battery, or reverse flow.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Many AMR devices can also capture interval data, and log meter events.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Advanced metering infrastructure, or AMI is the new term coined to represent the networking technology of fixed network meter systems that go beyond AMR into remote utility management.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The meters in an AMI system are often referred to as smart meters, since they often can use collected data based on programmed logic.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The Automatic Meter Reading Association (AMRA) endorses the National Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners (NARUC) resolution to eliminate regulatory barriers to the broad implementation of advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The resolution, passed in February 2007, acknowledged the role of AMI in supporting the implementation of dynamic pricing and the resulting benefits to consumers.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The resolution further identified the value of AMI in achieving significant utility operational cost savings in the areas of outage management, revenue protection and asset management.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The resolution also called for AMI business case analysis to identify cost-effective deployment strategies, endorsed timely cost recovery for prudently incurred AMI expenditures and made additional recommendations on rate making and tax treatment of such investments.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Advanced metering systems can provide benefits for utilities, retail providers and customers.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Benefits will be recognized by the utilities with increased efficiencies, outage detection, tamper notification and reduced labor cost as a result of automating reads, connections and disconnects.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Retail providers will be able to offer new innovative products in addition to customizing packages for their customers.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In addition, with the meter data being readily available, more flexible billing cycles would be available to their customers instead of following the standard utility read cycles.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] With timely usage information available to the customer, benefits will be seen through opportunities to manage their energy consumption and change from one REP to another with actual meter data.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Because of these benefits, many utilities are moving towards implementing some types of AMR solutions.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In many cases, smart metering is required by law (e.g.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The benefits of smart metering for the utility.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The benefits of smart metering for the customer.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Construction practices, weather, and the need for information drive utilities in different parts of the world towards AMR at different rates.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In the US, there have been significant fixed network deployments of both RF based and PLC based technologies.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Some countries have either deployed or plan to deploy AMR systems throughout the entire country.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] By using a combination of AMR and energy analytics reports, SPAR were able to reduce energy consumption by 20%.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] AMI in Australia has grown from both government policy which sought to rectify observed market inefficiencies, and distribution businesses who looked to gain operational efficiencies.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In July 2008, there was a mandated program being planned in Victoria for the deployment of 2.6 million meters over a 4-year period.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The anticipated peak installation rate of AMI meters was 5,000 per day across Victoria.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The program governance was provided by an industry steering committee.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In 2009 the Victorian Auditor General undertook a review of the program and found that there were "significant inadequacies" in advice to Government and that project governance "has not been appropriate".
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] With the growing adoption of AMI meters and systems, AMR has been in decline in the U.S. electric utility sector.
[src:mbus-metering/automatic-meter-reading] However, in the gas and water sectors, where it tends to be more expensive and complicated to replace meters, AMR remains prevalent, and some utilities continue to invest in new AMR meter deployments.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] A **data logger** (also **datalogger** or **data recorder**) is an electronic device that records data over time or about location either with a built-in instrument or sensor or via external instruments and sensors.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Increasingly, but not entirely, they are based on a digital processor (or computer), and called digital data loggers (DDL).
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] They generally are small, battery-powered, portable, and equipped with a microprocessor, internal memory for data storage, and sensors.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Some data loggers interface with a personal computer and use software to activate the data logger and view and analyze the collected data, while others have a local interface device (keypad, LCD) and can be used as a stand-alone device.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Data loggers vary from general-purpose devices for various measurement applications to very specific devices for measuring in one environment or application type only.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] While it is common for general-purpose types to be programmable, many remain static machines with only a limited number or no changeable parameters.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Electronic data loggers have replaced chart recorders in many applications.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] One primary benefit of using data loggers is their ability to automatically collect data on a 24-hour basis.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Upon activation, data loggers are typically deployed and left unattended to measure and record information for the duration of the monitoring period.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] This allows for a comprehensive, accurate picture of the environmental conditions being monitored, such as air temperature and relative humidity.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] The cost of data loggers has been declining over the years as technology improves and costs are reduced.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Simple single-channel data loggers can cost as little as $25, while more complicated loggers may cost hundreds or thousands of dollars.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Standardization of protocols and data formats has been a problem but is now growing in the industry and XML, JSON, and YAML are increasingly being adopted for data exchange.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] The development of the Semantic Web and the Internet of Things is likely to accelerate this present trend.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Several protocols have been standardized including a smart protocol, SDI-12, that allows some instrumentation to be connected to a variety of data loggers.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] The use of this standard has not gained much acceptance outside the environmental industry.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] SDI-12 also supports multi-drop instruments.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Some data logging companies support the MODBUS standard.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] This has been used traditionally in the industrial control area, and many industrial instruments support this communication standard.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Another multi-drop protocol that is now starting to become more widely used is based upon CAN-Bus (ISO 11898).
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Some data loggers use a flexible scripting environment to adapt to various non-standard protocols.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] The terms data logging and data acquisition are often used interchangeably.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] However, in a historical context, they are quite different.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] A data logger is a data acquisition system, but a data acquisition system is not necessarily a data logger.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Data Loggers are changing more rapidly now than ever before.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] The original model of a stand-alone data logger is changed to one of a device that collects data but also has access to wireless communications for alarming of events, automatic reporting of data, and remote control.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Data loggers are beginning to serve web pages for current readings, e-mail their alarms, and FTP their daily results into databases or direct to the users.
[src:mbus-metering/data-logger] Very recently, there is a trend to move away from proprietary products with commercial software to open-source software and hardware devices.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] The M-Bus was developed to fill the need for a system for the networking and remote reading of utility meters, for example to measure the consumption of gas or water in the home.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] This bus fulfills the special requirements of remotely powered or battery-driven systems, including consumer utility meters.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] When interrogated, the meters deliver the data they have collected to a common master, such as a hand-held computer, connected at periodic intervals to read all utility meters of a building.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] An alternative method of collecting data centrally is to transmit meter readings via a modem.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Other applications for the M-Bus such as alarm systems, flexible illumination installations, heating control, etc. are suitable.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Since no bus system was available for the requirements of meter reading, the M-Bus was developed by Horst Ziegler of the University of Paderborn in cooperation with Texas Instruments Deutschland GmbH and Techem GmbH.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] The concept was based on the ISO-OSI Reference Model, in order to realize an open system which could use almost any desired protocol.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Since the M-Bus is not a network, and therefore does not – among other things – need a transport or session layer, the levels four to six of the OSI model are empty.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Therefore, only the physical, the data link, the network and the application layer are provided with functions.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] M-Bus connection is called M-Bus or HAN (Home Area Network) consumer connection.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] M-Bus uses two-wire telephone cable (JYStY 1x*2x*0.8 mm or similar, 73 ohm/km, 120 nF/km) maximum length of 350 meters when using nominal transfer speeds 300 and 9600 baud.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Lowering the speed up to 1000 meter cable can be used.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] There is no standardized connector, but RJ11 and RJ12 Modular connectors are used by meter manufacturers.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] The master communication uses voltage signaling, where 1 (idle state, mark) is the bus nominal 36 volts, 0 (space) drops the voltage to 24 volts (V).
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] As bus voltage can vary with length and load, the signal is specified as 1 for bus voltage drop less than 5.5 V, 0 for drop higher than 8.2 V.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Slaves communicate by current consumption, where 1 (idle state, mark) is less than 1.5 milliamperes (mA), 0 (space) raises current to 11–20 mA.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] The signal is specified as the at least 11 mA current increase.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] The slaves are connected via diode bridge and can use either polarity of the wires.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] To protect the bus against shortcircuited slaves, a 430 ohm is connected in series at each slave (or, two 215 ohm resistors, one for each wire).
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Most slaves use at most this, some can need two units (3 mA).
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Masters can provide type-dependent number of load units, and usually visually indicate overload.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] The data link protocol is described by IEC 870-5, or its updated version, IEC 60870-5.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] The data are sent in serial form, at speed between 300 and 9600 bit/s (some variants may operate up to 19200 or 38400 bit/s), using one start bit, one stop bit, and even parity (8e1).
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] The least significant bit is sent first.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] When sending packets ("telegrams"), there is no pause between stop and subsequent start bit.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Suggested speeds are 300, 2400, 9600, and with newer hardware 38400 bit/s, while 2400 bit/s is most common.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Devices with different baudrates can coexist on the same bus.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Some devices use Automatic Baud Rate Detection (ABR) or autobauding.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] CI-field is the control information field.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Length field in control/long frame is sent twice.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Minimum value is 0x03, as C-field, A-field and CI-field are mandatory parts of the payload.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Slaves respond only to correctly formed packets that match their address.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Any fault is indicated by lack of response.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Absence of response is defined as no response for 330 bit periods (35 ms for 9600 bit/s, 1.1 s for 300 bit/s) plus 50 ms.
[src:mbus-metering/meter-bus] Numerical values are usually sent in BCD format.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] A **smart meter** is an electronic device that records information—such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor—and communicates the information to the consumer and electricity suppliers.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) differs from automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The term *smart meter* often refers to an electricity meter, but it also may mean a device measuring natural gas, water or district heating consumption.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] More generally, a smart meter is an electronic device that records information such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters communicate the information to the consumer for greater clarity of consumption behavior, and electricity suppliers for system monitoring and customer billing.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters typically record energy near real-time, and report regularly, in short intervals throughout the day.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters enable two-way communication between the meter and the central system.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters may be part of a *smart grid*, but do not themselves constitute a smart grid.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) differs from Automated Meter Reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Communications from the meter to the network may be wireless, or via fixed wired connections such as power-line communication (PLC).
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Similar meters, usually referred to as interval or time-of-use meters, have existed for years, but smart meters usually involve real-time or near real-time sensors, power outage notification, and power quality monitoring.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] These additional features are more than simple AMR.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] They are similar in many respects to AMI meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Interval and time-of-use meters historically have been installed to measure commercial and industrial customers, but may not have automatic reading.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Research by the UK consumer group, showed that as many as one in three confuse smart meters with energy monitors, also known as in-home display monitors.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In 1972, Theodore Paraskevakos, while working with Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system that used digital transmission for security, fire, and medical alarm systems as well as meter reading capabilities.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This technology was a spin-off from the automatic telephone line identification system, now known as Caller ID.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In 1977, he launched Metretek, Inc., which developed and produced the first smart meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The installed base of smart meters in Europe at the end of 2008 was about 39 million units, according to analyst firm Berg Insight.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Globally, Pike Research found that smart meter shipments were 17.4 million units for the first quarter of 2011.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Visiongain determined that the value of the global smart meter market would reach US$7 billion in 2012.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Tahir Mahmood, researchers of University of Engineering & Technology Taxila, Pakistan, introduced the concept of Smart Energy Meters in 2013.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] As of January 2018, over 99 million electricity meters were deployed across the European Union, with an estimated 24 million more to be installed by the end of 2020.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The European Commission DG Energy estimates the 2020 installed base to have required €18.8 billion in investment, growing to €40.7 billion by 2030, with a total deployment of 266 million smart meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] By the end of 2018, the U.S. had over 86 million smart meters installed.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In 2017, there were 665 million smart meters installed globally.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Revenue generation is expected to grow from $12.8 billion in 2017 to $20 billion by 2022.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Since the inception of electricity deregulation and market-driven pricing throughout the world, utilities have been looking for a means to match consumption with generation.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Non-smart electrical and gas meters only measure total consumption, providing no information of when the energy was consumed.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters provide a way of measuring electricity consumption in near real-time.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This allows utility companies to charge different prices for consumption according to the time of day and the season.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] It also facilitates more accurate cash-flow models for utilities.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Since smart meters can be read remotely, labor costs are reduced for utilities.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart metering offers potential benefits to customers.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] With regards to consumption reduction, this is critical for understanding the benefits of smart meters because the relatively small percentage benefits in terms of savings are multiplied by millions of users.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters for water consumption can also provide detailed and timely information about customer water use and early notification of possible water leaks in their premises.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Electricity consumption, and hence pricing, usually peaks at certain predictable times of the day and the season.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In particular, if generation is constrained, prices can rise when power from other jurisdictions or more costly generation is brought online.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] A 2013 academic study based on existing trials showed that homeowners' electricity consumption on average is reduced by approximately 3-5% when provided with real-time feedback.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Another advantage of smart meters that benefits both customers and the utility is the monitoring capability they provide for the whole electrical system.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] As part of an AMI, utilities can use the real-time data from smart meters measurements related to current, voltage, and power factor to detect system disruptions more quickly, allowing immediate corrective action to minimize customer impact such as blackouts.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters also help utilities understand the power grid needs with more granularity than legacy meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This greater understanding facilitates system planning to meet customer energy needs while reducing the likelihood of additional infrastructure investments, which eliminates unnecessary spending or energy cost increases.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] As a result, smart meters are considered an essential technology to the decarbonisation of the energy system.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Government agencies and utilities are turning toward advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) systems as part of larger "smart grid" initiatives.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] AMI extends automatic meter reading (AMR) technology by providing two-way meter communications, allowing commands to be sent toward the home for multiple purposes, including time-based pricing information, demand-response actions, or remote service disconnects.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Wireless technologies are critical elements of the neighborhood network, aggregating a mesh configuration of up to thousands of meters for back haul to the utility's IT headquarters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The network between the measurement devices and business systems allows the collection and distribution of information to customers, suppliers, utility companies, and service providers.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This enables these businesses to participate in demand response services.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Consumers can use the information provided by the system to change their normal consumption patterns to take advantage of lower prices.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Pricing can be used to curb the growth of peak demand consumption.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] AMI differs from traditional automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communications with the meter.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Systems only capable of meter readings do not qualify as AMI systems.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Together, these components help utilities and consumers monitor and manage energy use efficiently, supporting smarter grid management.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Communication is a cornerstone of smart meter technology, enabling reliable and secure data transmission to central systems.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] However, the diversity of environments in which smart meters operate presents significant challenges.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] stands out among smart metering connectivity technologies because it leverages existing electrical power infrastructure for data transmission.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Unlike cellular, radio-frequency (RF), or Wi-Fi-based solutions, PLC does not require building or maintaining separate communication networks, making it inherently more cost-effective and easier to scale.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] G3-PLC supports IPv6-based communications and adaptive data rates, providing robust performance even in noisy environments, while PRIME (PoweRline Intelligent Metering Evolution) focuses on efficient, high-speed communication with low-cost implementation.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] like Europe, South America, and parts of Asia where dense infrastructure supports its use.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Utilities favor PLC for its reliability in urban environments and for connecting large numbers of meters within smart grid networks.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] An important feature of G3-PLC and PRIME is their ability to enable mesh networking (also called multi-hop), where smart meters act as repeaters for other meters in the network.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This functionality allows meters to relay data from neighboring meters to ensure that the information reaches the Data Concentrator Unit (DCU), even if direct communication is not possible due to distance or signal obstructions.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This approach enhances network reliability and coverage, particularly in dense urban environments or geographically challenging areas.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The challenges faced by rural utilities differ significantly from those of urban counterparts or utilities in remote, mountainous, or poorly serviced areas.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters often extend their functionality through integration into **Home Area Networks (HANs)**.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Technologies used in HANs vary globally but typically include PLC, wireless ad hoc networks, and Zigbee.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] By leveraging appropriate connectivity solutions, smart meters can address environmental and infrastructural needs while delivering communication and enhanced functionality.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Electricity smart meters start to be utilized as gateways for gas and water meters, creating integrated smart metering systems.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In this configuration, gas and water meters communicate with the electricity meter using Wireless M-Bus (Wireless Meter-Bus), a European standard (EN 13757-4) designed for secure and efficient data transmission between utility meters and data collectors.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The electricity meter then aggregates this data and transmits it to the central utility network via Power Line Communication (PLC), which leverages existing electrical wiring for data transfer.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meter communication protocols are essential for enabling reliable, efficient, and secure data exchange between meters, utilities, and other components of advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] These protocols address the diverse requirements of global markets, supporting various communication methods, from optical ports and serial connections to power line communication (PLC) and wireless networks.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Below is an overview of key protocols, including ANSI standards widely used in North America, IEC protocols prevalent in Europe, the globally recognized OSGP for smart grid applications, and the PLC-focused Meters and More, each designed to meet specific needs in energy monitoring and management.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] "IEC 62056 is the most widely adopted protocol" for smart meter communication, enabling reliable, two-way data exchange within Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) systems.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] It encompasses the DLMS/COSEM protocol for structuring and managing metering data.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] "It is widely used because of its flexibility, scalability, and ability to support different communication media such as Power Line Communication (PLC), TCP/IP, and wireless networks.".
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] It also supports data transmission over serial connections using ASCII or binary formats, with physical media options such as modulated light (via LED and photodiode) or wired connections (typically EIA-485).
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] ANSI C12.18 is an ANSI Standard that describes a protocol used for two-way communications with a meter, mostly used in North American markets.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The C12.18 Standard is written specifically for meter communications via an ANSI Type 2 Optical Port, and specifies lower-level protocol details.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] ANSI C12.19 specifies the data tables that are used.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] ANSI C12.21 is an extension of C12.18 written for modem instead of optical communications, so it is better suited to automatic meter reading.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] ANSI C12.22 is the communication protocol for remote communications.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The Open Smart Grid Protocol (OSGP) is a family of specifications published by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) used in conjunction with the ISO/IEC 14908 control networking standard for smart metering and smart grid applications.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Millions of smart meters based on OSGP are deployed worldwide.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] On July 15, 2015, the OSGP Alliance announced the release of a new security protocol (OSGP-AES-128-PSK) and its availability from OSGP vendors.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This deprecated the original OSGP-RC4-PSK security protocol which had been identified to be vulnerable.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] "Meters and More was created in 2010 from the coordinated work between Enel and Endesa to adopt, maintain and evolve the field-proven Meters and More open communication protocol for smart grid solutions." .
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In 2010, the Meters and More Association was established to promote the protocol globally, ensuring interoperability and efficiency in power line communication (PLC)-based smart metering systems.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Meters and More is an open communication protocol designed for advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] It facilitates reliable, high-speed data exchange over PLC networks, focusing on energy monitoring, demand response, and secure two-way communication between utilities and consumers.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Unlike DLMS/COSEM, which is a globally standardized and versatile protocol supporting multiple utilities (electricity, gas, and water), Meters and More is tailored specifically for PLC-based systems, emphasizing efficiency, reliability, and ease of deployment in electricity metering.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] There is a growing trend toward the use of TCP/IP technology as a common communication platform for Smart Meter applications, so that utilities can deploy multiple communication systems, while using IP technology as a common management platform.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] A universal metering interface would allow for development and mass production of smart meters and smart grid devices prior to the communication standards being set, and then for the relevant communication modules to be easily added or switched when they are.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This would lower the risk of investing in the wrong standard as well as permit a single product to be used globally even if regional communication standards vary.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI), the server infrastructure is crucial for managing, storing, and processing the large volumes of data generated by smart meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This infrastructure ensures seamless communication between smart meters, utility providers, and end-users, supporting real-time monitoring, billing, and grid management.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] A Data Concentrator Unit (DCU) aggregates data from multiple smart meters within a localized area (e.g., a neighborhood or building) before transmitting it to the central server.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Data concentrators reduce the communication load on the network and help overcome connectivity challenges by acting as intermediaries between smart meters and the head-end system (HES).
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The HES is responsible for collecting, validating, and managing data received from data concentrators and smart meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] It serves as the central communication hub, facilitating two-way communication between the smart meters and the utility's central servers.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The HES supports meter configuration, firmware updates, and real-time data retrieval, ensuring data integrity and security.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] is a specialized software platform that stores and processes large volumes of meter data collected by the HES.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Key functions of the MDMS include data validation, estimation, and editing, as well as billing preparation, load analysis, and anomaly detection.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] ), and demand response systems, to enable efficient energy management.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Data analytics for smart meters leverages machine learning to extract insights from energy consumption data.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Key applications include demand forecasting, dynamic pricing, Energy Disaggregation, and fault detection, enabling optimized grid performance and personalized energy management.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] These techniques drive efficiency, cost savings, and sustainability in modern energy systems.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] "Energy Disaggregation, or the breakdown of your energy use based on specific appliances or devices", is an exploratory technique for analyzing energy consumption in households, commercial buildings, and industrial settings.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] By using data from a single energy meter, it employs algorithms and machine learning to estimate individual appliance usage without separate monitors.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Known as Non-Intrusive Load Monitoring (NILM), this emerging method offers insights into energy efficiency, helping users optimize usage and reduce costs.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] While promising, energy disaggregation is still being refined for accuracy and scalability as part of smart energy management innovations.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The other critical technology for smart meter systems is the information technology at the utility that integrates the Smart Meter networks with utility applications, such as billing and CIS.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This includes the Meter Data Management system.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] It also is essential for smart grid implementations that power line communication (PLC) technologies used within the home over a Home Area Network (HAN), are standardized and compatible.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The HAN allows HVAC systems and other household appliances to communicate with the smart meter, and from there to the utility.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Currently there are several broadband or narrowband standards in place, or being developed, that are not yet compatible.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] To address this issue in the United States, the National Institute for Standards and Technology (NIST) established the PAP15 group, which studies and recommends coexistence mechanisms with a focus on the harmonization of PLC Standards for the HAN.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The objective of the group is to ensure that all PLC technologies selected for the HAN coexist as a minimum.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The two leading broadband PLC technologies selected are the HomePlug AV / IEEE 1901 and ITU-T G.hn technologies.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Technical working groups within these organizations are working to develop appropriate coexistence mechanisms.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The HomePlug Powerline Alliance has developed a new standard for smart grid HAN communications called the HomePlug Green PHY specification.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] It is interoperable and coexistent with the widely deployed HomePlug AV technology and with the latest IEEE 1901 global Standard and is based on Broadband OFDM technology.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] ITU-T commissioned in 2010 a new project called G.hnem, to address the home networking aspects of energy management, built upon existing Low Frequency Narrowband OFDM technologies.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Some groups have expressed concerns regarding the cost, health, fire risk, security and privacy effects of smart meters and the remote controllable "kill switch" that is included with most of them.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Many of these concerns regard wireless-only smart meters with no home energy monitoring or control or safety features.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Metering-only solutions, while popular with utilities because they fit existing business models and have cheap up-front capital costs, often result in such "backlash".
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Often the entire smart grid and smart building concept is discredited in part by confusion about the difference between home control and home area network technology and AMI.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The (now former) attorney general of Connecticut has stated that he does not believe smart meters provide any financial benefit to consumers, however, the cost of the installation of the new system is absorbed by those customers.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters expose the power grid to cyberattacks that could lead to power outages, both by cutting off people's electricity and by overloading the grid.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] However many cybersecurity experts state that smart meters of the UK and Germany have relatively high cybersecurity and that any such attack there would thus require extraordinarily high efforts or financial resources.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The EU Cybersecurity Act took effect in June 2019, which includes Directive on Security Network and Information Systems establishing notification and security requirements for operators of essential services.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Through the Smartgrid Cybersecurity Committee, the U.S.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Department of Energy published cybersecurity guidelines for grid operators in 2010 and updated them in 2014.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Implementing security protocols that protect these devices from malicious attacks has been problematic, due to their limited computational resources and long operational life.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The current version of IEC 62056 includes the possibility to encrypt, authenticate, or sign the meter data.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] One proposed smart meter data verification method involves analyzing the network traffic in real-time to detect anomalies using an Intrusion Detection System (IDS).
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] By identifying exploits as they are being leveraged by attackers, an IDS mitigates the suppliers' risks of energy theft by consumers and denial-of-service attacks by hackers.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Energy utilities must choose between a centralized IDS, embedded IDS, or dedicated IDS depending on the individual needs of the utility.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Researchers have found that for a typical advanced metering infrastructure, the centralized IDS architecture is superior in terms of cost efficiency and security gains.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In the United Kingdom, the Data Communication Company, which transports the commands from the supplier to the smart meter, performs an additional anomaly check on commands issued (and signed) by the energy supplier.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] According to a report published by Brian Krebs, in 2009 a Puerto Rico electricity supplier asked the FBI to investigate large-scale thefts of electricity related to its smart meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The FBI found that former employees of the power company and the company that made the meters were being paid by consumers to reprogram the devices to show incorrect results, as well as teaching people how to do it themselves.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Several hacking tools that allow security researchers and penetration testers verify the security of electric utility smart meters have been released so far.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Most health concerns about the meters arise from the pulsed radiofrequency (RF) radiation emitted by wireless smart meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Members of the California State Assembly asked the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST) to study the issue of potential health impacts from smart meters, in particular whether current FCC standards are protective of public health.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The CCST report in April 2011 found no health impacts, based both on lack of scientific evidence of harmful effects from radio frequency (RF) waves and that the RF exposure of people in their homes to smart meters is likely to be minuscule compared to RF exposure to cell phones and microwave ovens.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Daniel Hirsch, retired director of the Program on Environmental and Nuclear Policy at UC Santa Cruz, criticized the CCST report on the grounds that it did not consider studies that suggest the potential for non-thermal health effects such as latent cancers from RF exposure.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has adopted recommended Permissible Exposure Limit (PEL) for all RF transmitters (including smart meters) operating at frequencies of 300 kHz to 100 GHz.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] These limits, based on field strength and power density, are below the levels of RF radiation that are hazardous to human health.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Other studies substantiate the finding of the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST).
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In 2011, the Electric Power Research Institute performed a study to gauge human exposure to smart meters as compared to the FCC PEL.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The report found that most smart meters only transmit RF signals 1% of the time or less.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] At this rate, and at a distance of 1 foot from the meter, RF exposure would be at a rate of 0.14% of the FCC PEL.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] An indirect potential for harm to health by smart meters is that they enable energy companies to disconnect consumers remotely, typically in response to difficulties with payment.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This can cause health problems to vulnerable people in financial difficulty; in addition to denial of heat, lighting, and use of appliances, there are people who depend on power to use medical equipment essential for life.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] While there may be legal protections in place to protect the vulnerable, many people in the UK were disconnected in violation of the rules.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Issues surrounding smart meters causing fires have been reported, particularly involving the manufacturer Sensus.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] PECO Energy Company replaced the Sensus meters it had deployed in the Philadelphia, US region after reports that a number of the units had overheated and caused fires.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In July 2014, SaskPower, the province-run utility company of the Canadian province of Saskatchewan, halted its roll-out of Sensus meters after similar, isolated incidents were discovered.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Shortly afterward, Portland General Electric announced that it would replace 70,000 smart meters that had been deployed in the state of Oregon after similar reports.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The company noted that it had been aware of the issues since at least 2013, and they were limited to specific models it had installed between 2010 and 2012.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] On July 30, 2014, after a total of eight recent fire incidents involving the meters, SaskPower was ordered by the Government of Saskatchewan to immediately end its smart meter program, and remove the 105,000 smart meters it had installed.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] One technical reason for privacy concerns is that these meters send detailed information about how much electricity is being used each time.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] More frequent reports provide more detailed information.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Infrequent reports may be of little benefit for the provider, as it doesn't allow as good demand management in the response of changing needs for electricity.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] On the other hand, widespread reports would allow the utility company to infer behavioral patterns for the occupants of a house, such as when the members of the household are probably asleep or absent.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Furthermore, the fine-grained information collected by smart meters raises growing concerns of privacy invasion due to personal behavior exposure (private activity, daily routine, etc.).
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Current trends are to increase the frequency of reports.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] A solution that benefits both provider and user privacy would be to adapt the interval dynamically.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Another solution involves energy storage installed at the household used to reshape the energy consumption profile.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In British Columbia the electric utility is government-owned and as such must comply with privacy laws that prevent the sale of data collected by smart meters; many parts of the world are serviced by private companies that are able to sell their data.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In Australia debt collectors can make use of the data to know when people are at home.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Used as evidence in a court case in Austin, Texas, police agencies secretly collected smart meter power usage data from thousands of residences to determine which used more power than "typical" to identify marijuana growing operations.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meter power data usage patterns can reveal much more than how much power is being used.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Research has demonstrated that smart meters sampling power levels at two-second intervals can reliably identify when different electrical devices are in use.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Reviews of smart meter programs, moratoriums, delays, and "opt-out" programs are some responses to the concerns of customers and government officials.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In response to residents who did not want a smart meter, in June 2012 a utility in Hawaii changed its smart meter program to "opt out".
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The utility said that once the smart grid installation project is nearing completion, KIUC may convert the deferral policy to an opt-out policy or program and may charge a fee to those members to cover the costs of servicing the traditional meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Any fee would require approval from the Hawaii Public Utilities Commission.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] After receiving numerous complaints about health, hacking, and privacy concerns with the wireless digital devices, the Public Utility Commission of the US state of Maine voted to allow customers to opt-out of the meter change at the cost of $12 a month.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In Connecticut, another US state to consider smart metering, regulators declined a request by the state's largest utility, Connecticut Light & Power, to install 1.2 million of the devices, arguing that the potential savings in electric bills do not justify the cost.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] CL&P already offers its customers time-based rates.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The state's Attorney General George Jepsen was quoted as saying the proposal would cause customers to spend upwards of $500 million on meters and get few benefits in return, a claim that Connecticut Light & Power disputed.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters allow dynamic pricing; it has been pointed out that, while this allows prices to be reduced at times of low demand, it can also be used to increase prices at peak times if all consumers have smart meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Additionally smart meters allow energy suppliers to switch customers to expensive prepay tariffs instantly in case of difficulties paying.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In the UK during a period of very high energy prices from 2021, companies were remotely switching smart meters from a credit tariff to an expensive prepay tariff which disconnects supplies unless credit has been purchased.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] While regulations do not permit this without appropriate precautions to help those in financial difficulties and to protect the vulnerable, the rules were often flouted.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] There are questions about whether electricity is or should be primarily a "when you need it" service where the inconvenience/cost-benefit ratio of time-shifting of loads is poor.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In the Chicago area, Commonwealth Edison ran a test installing smart meters on 8,000 randomly selected households together with variable rates and rebates to encourage cutting back during peak usage.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In *Crain's Chicago Business* article "Smart grid test underwhelms.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In the pilot, few power down to save money.", it was reported that fewer than 9% exhibited any amount of peak usage reduction and that the overall amount of reduction was "statistically insignificant".
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] This was from a report by the Electric Power Research Institute, a utility industry think tank who conducted the study and prepared the report.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] By 2016, the 7 million smart meters in Texas had not persuaded many people to check their energy data as the process was too complicated.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] A report from a parliamentary group in the UK suggests people who have smart meters installed are expected to save an average of £11 annually on their energy bills, much less than originally hoped.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The 2016 cost-benefit analysis was updated in 2019 and estimated a similar average saving.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The Australian Victorian Auditor-General found in 2015 that 'Victoria's electricity consumers will have paid an estimated $2.239 billion for metering services, including the rollout and connection of smart meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Smart meters can allow real-time pricing, and in theory this could help smooth power consumption as consumers adjust their demand in response to price changes.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In 2013, *Take Back Your Power*, an independent Canadian documentary directed by Josh del Sol was released describing "dirty electricity" and the aforementioned issues with smart meters.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The film explores the various contexts of the health, legal, and economic concerns.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] It features narration from the mayor of Peterborough, Ontario, Daryl Bennett, as well as American researcher De-Kun Li, journalist Blake Levitt, and Dr.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] It won a Leo Award for best feature-length documentary and the Annual Humanitarian Award from Indie Fest the following year.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Citizens Advice said in August 2018 that 80% of people with smart meters were happy with them.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Still, it had 3,000 calls in 2017 about problems.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] These related to first-generation smart meters losing their functionality, aggressive sales practices, and still having to send smart meter readings.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Ross Anderson of the Foundation for Information Policy Research has criticised the UK's program on the grounds that it is unlikely to lower energy consumption, is rushed and expensive, and does not promote metering competition.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The high number of SMETS1 meters installed has been criticized by Peter Earl, head of energy at the price comparison website comparethemarket.com.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] UK smart meters in southern England and the Midlands use the mobile phone network to communicate, so they do not work correctly when phone coverage is weak.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] A solution has been proposed, but was not operational as of March 2017.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In March 2018 the National Audit Office (NAO), which watches over public spending, opened an investigation into the smart meter program, which had cost £11bn by then, paid for by electricity users through higher bills.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The National Audit Office published the findings of its investigation in a report titled "Rolling out smart meters" published in November 2018.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The report, amongst other findings, indicated that the number of smart meters installed in the UK would fall materially short of the Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy (BEIS) original ambitions of all UK consumers having a smart meter installed by 2020.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] In September 2019, smart meter rollout in the UK was delayed for four years.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] Ross Anderson and Alex Henney wrote that "Ed Miliband cooked the books" to make a case for smart meters appear economically viable.
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] They say that the first three cost-benefit analyses of residential smart meters found that it would cost more than it would save, but "ministers kept on trying until they got a positive result...
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] To achieve 'profitability' the previous government stretched the assumptions shamelessly".
[src:mbus-metering/smart-meter] The Employment Appeal Tribunal found that the law was in contravention of the European Convention on Human Rights.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Sub-metering may also refer to the monitoring of the electrical consumption of individual equipment within a building, such as HVAC, indoor and outdoor lighting, refrigeration, kitchen equipment and more.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Typically a multi-tenant dwelling has either one master meter for the entire property or a meter for each building and the property is responsible for the entire utility bill.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Submetering allows property owners who supply utilities to their tenants the ability to account for each tenant's usage in measurable terms.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] By fairly billing each tenant for their portion, submetering promotes conservation and offsets the expense of bills generated from a master meter, maintenance and improvements for well water systems, lagoon, or septic systems.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Submetering is legally allowable in most states and municipalities, but owners should consult a Utility Management Vendor for assistance with local and state compliance and regulations.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Typical users of submetering are mobile home parks, apartments, condominiums, townhouses, student housing, and commercial areas.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Usually, utility submetering is placed in situations where the local utility cannot or will not individually meter the utility in question.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Municipal Utility companies are often reluctant to take on metering individual spaces for several reasons.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] One reason is that rental space tenants tend to be more transient and are more difficult to collect from.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] By billing only the owner, they can place liens on real property if not paid (as opposed to tenants they may not know exist or who have little to lose if they move without paying).
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Utilities also generally prefer not to have water meters beyond their easement (i.e., the property boundary), since leaks to a service line would be before the meter and could be of less concern to a property owner.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Other reasons include difficulty in getting access to meters for reading, or electrical systems and plumbing not suitable for submetering.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Before submetering, many landlords either included the utility cost in the bulk price of the rent or lease, or divided the utility usage among the tenants in some way such as equally, by square footage via allocation methods often called RUBS (Ratio Utility Billing System) or some other means.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Without a meter to measure individual usage, there is less incentive to identify building inefficiencies, since the other tenants or landlord may pay all or part of those costs.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Submetering creates awareness of water and Energy conservation because landlords and tenants are equally aware of what they will pay for these inefficiencies if they are not attended to.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Conservation also allows property owners to keep the cost of rent reasonable and fair for all units regardless of how much water or energy they consume.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] On the other hand, submetering provides an opportunity for building owners to shift their rising electricity costs to tenants who lack ownership or control over thermal efficiency of the structure, its insulation, windows, and major energy consuming appliances.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Landlords may attempt to deem their charges for electric service as "additional rent" making tenants subject to eviction for nonpayment of electric bills, which would not be possible if they were direct customers of the utility.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] The Ontario Energy Board in August 2009 nullified all landlord submetering and allowed future submetering only upon informed tenant consent, including provision of third party energy audits to tenants to enable them to judge the total cost of rent plus electricity.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Some submetering products connect with software that provides consumption data.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] This data provides users with the information to locate leaks and high-consumption areas.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Users can apply this data to implement conservation or renovation projects to lower usage & costs, meet government mandates, or participate in green building programs such as LEED and green globes.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] A submetering system typically includes a "master meter", which is owned by the utility supplying the water, electricity, or gas, with overall usage billed directly to the property owner.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] The property owner or manager then places their own private meters on individual tenant spaces to determine individual usage levels and bill each tenant for their share.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] In some cases, the landlord might add the usage cost to the regular rent or lease bill.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] In other cases, a third party might read, bill, and possibly even collect for the service.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Some of these companies also install and maintain meters and reading systems.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Panel or circuit submeters are used to measure resource use of the same system for added security, economic, reliability, and behavioral benefits.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] These provide important insights into resource consumption of building systems and equipment working in the same series.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Submeters can measure use of a single panel, or multiple points within a panel system using single-point, multi-point, and branch circuit submeters.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] The latest trend in submetering is Automatic Meter Reading, or AMR.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] This technology is used to get from meter reading to billing by an automated electronic means.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] This can be by handheld computers that collect data using touch wands, walk or drive-by radio, fixed network systems where the meter has a transmitter or transceiver that sends the data to a central location, or transmission via Wi-Fi, cellular, or Internet connections.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Although not technically submetering, an alternate method of utility cost allocation called RUBS (Ratio Utility Billing Systems) is sometimes used to allocate costs to tenants when true submetering is not practical or not possible due to plumbing or wiring constraints.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] This method divides utility costs by square footage, number of occupants, or some other combination of cost ratios.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] For example, central heating in apartment blocks in Belgium, Germany and Switzerland is sometimes submetered with liquid filled calibrated vials, known as heat cost allocators, attached to each of the heating radiators.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] The metering company visits the apartments about once a year and reads the liquid level and replaces the vials.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Some apartment owners have replaced the vials with electronic submeters that transmit temperature readings via radio to a master unit in each apartment.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] The master unit in turn transmits collated readings to the utility company, thereby saving both labour costs and inconvenience to both tenant and landlord.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] The master unit displays a number representing the current total of "heating value".
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] The concept of submetering was effectively "invented" sometime in the 1920s, when many laws currently affecting submetering were written.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Submetering was not widespread until the energy crisis in the mid-1970s, which prompted an increase in submetering for gas and electric usage.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Water submetering began its increase nationally in the mid-1990s when water and wastewater prices started rising.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] However, submetering really did not take a hold in the property management world until the late 1980s, with the ever increasing costs associated with utilities and a society more aware of environmental conservation.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] Utility submetering has its roots in Denmark.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] In 1902 two Danish brothers, Axel and Odin Clorius, established Clorius Controls.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] The company commenced work on developing and producing a range of self-acting temperature controllers.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] In 1924 Clorius received its first patent for a heat cost allocator.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] The device was meant to measure energy usage in apartments built with a common boiler heating system.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] The device was attached to each radiator in an apartment unit.
[src:mbus-metering/utility-submeter] By measuring energy usage at each radiator, a consumption-based utility bill could be prepared for each unit.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In most of the world water meters are calibrated in cubic metres (m3) or litres, but in the United States and some other countries water meters are calibrated in cubic feet (ft3) or US gallons on a mechanical or electronic register.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Modern meters typically can display rate-of-flow in addition to total volume.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Several types of water meters are in common use, and may be characterized by the flow measurement method, the type of end-user, the required flow rates, and accuracy requirements.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Water metering is changing rapidly with the advent of smart metering technology and various innovations.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In North America, standards for manufacturing water meters are set by the American Water Works Association.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Outside of North America, most countries use ISO standards.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] There are two common approaches to flow measurement: displacement and velocity, each making use of a variety of technologies.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Common displacement designs include oscillating piston and nutating disc meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Velocity-based designs include single- and multi-jet meters and turbine meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] There are also non-mechanical designs, for example, electromagnetic and ultrasonic meters, and meters designed for special uses.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Most meters in a typical water distribution system are designed to measure cold potable water only.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Specialty hot water meters are designed with materials that can withstand higher temperatures.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Meters for reclaimed water have special lavender register covers to signify that the water should not be used for drinking.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Additionally, there are electromechanical meters, like prepaid water meters and automatic meter reading meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The latter integrates an electronic measurement component and a LCD with a mechanical water meter.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Mechanical water meters normally use a reed switch, hall or photoelectric coding register as the signal output.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] After processing by the microcontroller unit (MCU) in the electronic module, the data are transmitted to the LCD or output to an information management system.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Water meters are generally owned, read and maintained by a public water provider such as a city, rural water association or private water company.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Displacement meters are commonly referred to as Positive Displacement, or "PD" meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Two common types are oscillating piston meters and nutating disk meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Either method relies on the water to physically displace the moving measuring element in direct proportion to the amount of water that passes through the meter.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The piston or disk moves a magnet that drives the register.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] PD meters are generally very accurate at the low-to-moderate flow rates typical of residential and small commercial users and commonly range in size from 5/8" to 2".
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Because displacement meters require that all water flows through the meter to "push" the measuring element, they generally are not practical in large commercial applications requiring high flow rates or low-pressure loss.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] PD meters normally have a built-in strainer to protect the measuring element from rocks or other debris that could stop or break the measuring element.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] PD meters normally have bronze, brass or plastic bodies with internal measuring chambers made of moulded plastics and stainless steel.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] A velocity-type meter measures the velocity of flow through a meter of known internal capacity.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The speed of the flow can then be converted into a volume of flow to determine the usage.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] There are several types of meters that measure water flow velocity, including jet meters (single-jet and multi-jet), turbine meters, propeller meters and mag meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Most velocity-based meters have an adjustment vane for calibrating the meter to the required accuracy.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Multi-jet meters are very accurate in small sizes and are commonly used in 5⁄8 in (16 mm) to 2 in (51 mm) sizes for residential and small commercial users.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Multi-jet meters use multiple ports surrounding an internal chamber to create multiple jets of water against a turbine, whose rotation speed depends on the velocity of water flow.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Multi-jets are very accurate at low flow rates, but there are no large size meters since they do not have the straight-through flow path needed for the high flow rates used in large pipe diameters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Multi-jet meters generally have an internal strainer element that can protect the jet ports from getting clogged.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Multi-jet meters normally have bronze alloy bodies or outer casings, with internal measuring parts made from modern thermoplastics and stainless steel.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Turbine meters are less accurate than displacement and jet meters at low flow rates, but the measuring element does not occupy or severely restrict the entire path of flow.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The flow direction is generally straight through the meter, allowing for higher flow rates and less pressure loss than displacement-type meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] They are the meter of choice for large commercial users, fire protection and as master meters for the water distribution system.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Strainers are generally required to be installed in front of the meter to protect the measuring element from gravel or other debris that could enter the water distribution system.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Turbine meters are generally available for 1+1⁄2 in (38 mm) to 12 in (300 mm) or higher pipe sizes.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Turbine meter bodies are commonly made of bronze, cast iron or ductile iron.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Internal turbine elements can be plastic or non-corrosive metal alloys.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] They are accurate in normal working conditions but are greatly affected by the flow profile and fluid conditions.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] A compound meter is used where high flow rates are necessary, but where at times there are also smaller rates of flow that need to be accurately measured.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Compound meters have two measuring elements and a check valve to regulate flow between them.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] At high flow rates, water is normally diverted primarily or completely to the high flow element.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The high flow element is typically a turbine meter.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] When flow rates drop to where the high flow element cannot measure accurately, a check valve closes to divert water to a smaller element that can measure the lower flow rates accurately.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The low flow element is typically a multi-jet or PD meter.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] By adding the values registered by the high and low elements, the utility has a record of the total consumption of water flowing through the meter.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Magnetic flow meters, commonly referred to as "mag meters", are technically a velocity-type water meter, except that they use electromagnetic properties to determine the water flow velocity, rather than the mechanical means used by jet and turbine meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Mag meters use the physics principle of Faraday's law of induction for measurement and require AC or DC electricity from a power line or battery to operate the electromagnets.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Since mag meters have no mechanical measuring element, they normally have the advantage of being able to measure flow in either direction, and use electronics for measuring and totalizing the flow.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Mag meters can also be useful for measuring raw (untreated/unfiltered) water and waste-water since there is no mechanical measuring element to get clogged or damaged by debris flowing through the meter.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Strainers are not required with mag meters since there is no measuring element in the stream of flow that could be damaged.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Since stray electrical energy flowing through the flow tube can cause inaccurate readings, most mag meters are installed with either grounding rings or grounding electrodes to divert stray electricity away from the electrodes used to measure the flow inside the flow tube.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Ultrasonic water meters use one or more ultrasonic transducer to send ultrasonic sound waves through the fluid to determine the velocity of the water.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Since the cross-sectional area of the meter body is a fixed and known value, when the velocity of water is detected, the volume of water passing through the meter can be calculated with very high accuracy.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Because of water density changes with temperature, most ultrasonic water meters also measure the water temperature as a component of the volume calculation.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Ultrasonic meters may either be of flow-through or "clamp-on" design.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Flow-through designs are those where the water passes directly through the meter, and are typically found in residential or commercial applications.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Clamp-on designs are generally used for larger diameters where the sensors are mounted to the exterior of pipes, etc.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Ultrasonic water meters are highly accurate devices, with residential models capable of measuring flow rates as low as 1 liter per hour (L/h).
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] They feature wide flow measurement ranges, require minimal maintenance, and have long lifespans due to the absence of internal mechanical components that could wear out over time.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] This design ensures stable long-term operation and reduces the need for maintenance.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Although relatively new to some markets, including the American water utility sector, ultrasonic water meters have been well-established in Europe, Asia, and other regions.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Their growing popularity is driven by the increasing demand for reliable, low-maintenance, and durable metering solutions suitable for diverse climates and water supply conditions.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Furthermore, the integration of smart meter technology with ultrasonic systems is accelerating their adoption worldwide, as utility providers seek more efficient and accurate data collection methods.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] A Coriolis water meter is a precision instrument used to measure the mass flow rate and density of fluids, including water, by utilizing the Coriolis effect.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Unlike traditional mechanical meters with moving parts, Coriolis meters use oscillating tubes through which the fluid flows.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] As the fluid passes through the tubes, it induces a phase shift in the oscillation, which is detected by sensors and is directly proportional to the mass flow rate.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Additionally, the meter can determine the fluid's density by analyzing the natural frequency of the oscillating tubes.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] This dual measurement capability provides high accuracy and reliability, making Coriolis meters particularly suitable for industrial applications requiring precise flow measurements.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In addition, "Coriolis meters have a wide, dynamic range due to the linear nature of the signal created while measuring flow." However, their high cost often limits their use in residential or municipal water metering.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The dimensions of water meters, including tube length and diameter, are standardized to ensure compatibility with plumbing systems and compliance with regulatory frameworks.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] These dimensions are typically defined in terms of **nominal pipe size (NPS)** in the United States and **nominal diameter (DN)** in Europe, with corresponding measurements in inches and millimeters, respectively.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Installation lengths are also standardized, differing between the United States and Europe to ensure interchangeability within regional plumbing systems.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] There are several types of registers on water meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] A standard register normally has a dial similar to a clock, with gradations around the perimeter to indicate the measuring unit and the amount of water used, if less than the lowest digit in a display similar to the odometer wheels in a car, their sum is the total volume used.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Modern registers are normally driven by a magnetic coupling between a magnet in the measuring chamber attached to the measuring element and another attached to the bottom of the register.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Gears in the register convert the motion of the measuring element to the proper usage increment for display on the sweep hand and the odometer-style wheels.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Many registers also have a leak detector.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] This is a small visible disk or hand that is geared closer to the rotation speed of the drive magnet, so that very small flows that would be visually undetectable on the regular sweep hand can be seen.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] With Automatic Meter Reading, manufacturers have developed pulse or encoder registers to produce electronic output for radio transmitters, reading storage devices, and data logging devices.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Pulse meters send a digital or analog electronic pulse to a recording device.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Encoder registers have an electronic means permitting an external device to interrogate the register to obtain either the position of the wheels or a stored electronic reading.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Frequent transmissions of consumption data can be used to give smart meter functionality.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] There are also some specialized types of registers such as meters with an LCD instead of mechanical wheels, and registers to output data or pulses to a variety of recording and controller devices.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] For industrial applications, the output is often 4-20 mA analog for recording or controlling different flow rates in addition to totalization.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Different size meters indicate different resolutions of the reading.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] One rotation of the sweep hand may be equivalent to 10 gallons or to 1,000 gallons (1 to 100 ft3, 0.1 to 10 m3).
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] If one rotation of the hand represents 10 gallons, the meter has a 10-gallon sweep.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Sometimes the last number(s) of the wheel display are non-rotating or printed on the dial face.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The fixed zero number(s) are represented by the position of the rotating sweep hand.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] For example, if one rotation of the hand is 10 gallons, the sweep hand is on 7, and the wheel display shows 123456 plus a fixed zero, the actual total usage would be 1,234,567 gallons.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In the United States most utilities bill only to the nearest 100 or 1,000 gallons (10 to 100 ft3, 1 to 10 m3), and often only read the leftmost 4 or 5 numbers on the display wheels.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Using the above example, they would read and bill 1,234, rounding to 1,234,000 gallons based on a 1,000-gallon billing resolution.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The most common rounding for a particular size meter is often indicated by differently coloured number wheels, the ones ignored being black, and the ones used for billing being white.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Smart metering technologies for water meters refer to advanced systems that enable real-time monitoring, data collection, and analysis of water usage through digital and connected devices.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Unlike traditional mechanical water meters, smart meters are equipped with electronic components that measure water flow and transmit the data wirelessly to utilities and consumers.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Key technologies include Automated Meter Reading (AMR), which provides one-way communication to collect usage data, and Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI), which supports two-way communication for enhanced features such as remote monitoring, leak detection, and dynamic billing.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Smart water meters are integrated with Internet of Things (IoT) platforms, allowing for more efficient water management, reduced waste, and improved customer engagement.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Radio Frequency (RF) technologies form the backbone of smart metering systems by enabling wireless communication between meters and utility networks.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Application-layer protocols operating above RF communication technologies to standardize data exchange, ensure interoperability, and enhance device functionality.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] These protocols enable integration of meters into broader utility and Internet of Things (IoT) ecosystems.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] DLMS/COSEM (Device Language Message Specification/Companion Specification for Energy Metering) is one of the most widely adopted protocols in smart metering.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] It provides a flexible and standardized framework for data exchange between metering devices and utility systems.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The protocol supports various communication technologies, including RF, wired, and cellular networks, and facilitates secure data transfer, structured data management, and remote monitoring.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] LwM2M (Lightweight Machine to Machine) is a protocol specifically designed for IoT devices, offering efficient resource management and secure communication over constrained networks.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Its lightweight design makes it ideal for smart water meters and other low-power devices.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] LwM2M supports remote configuration, firmware updates, and real-time monitoring, enabling enhanced functionality and scalability in metering systems.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Other application-layer protocols, such as MQTT (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport) and CoAP (Constrained Application Protocol), are also utilized in smart metering systems, particularly in IoT-centric deployments.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] These protocols focus on low-bandwidth, high-efficiency communication, ensuring reliable data exchange in diverse environments.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] A smart water metering system integrates advanced water meters, communication networks, and centralized platforms like the Head-End System (HES) and Meter Data Management System (MDMS).
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Smart meters collect data on water usage, pressure, and anomalies, transmitting it through wireless networks.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The HES aggregates and validates this data, forwarding it to the MDMS, which performs advanced analytics, trend reporting, and billing integration.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] A WMBUS Gateway (Wireless M-Bus Gateway) is a communication device that enables remote reading of water meters by bridging the gap between the water meters equipped with Wireless M-Bus communication modules and centralized data collection systems.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The gateway typically operates on standard frequencies such as 868 MHz (Europe) or other ISM bands.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In some cases, electricity meters with integrated communication modules are also utilized as fixed gateways to collect data from nearby water and gas meters, leveraging their existing infrastructure to minimize deployment costs.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The collected data is then transmitted to a central server via technologies like GSM, GPRS, LTE, or Ethernet for analysis and management.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Water metering is common for residential and commercial drinking water supply in many countries, as well as for industrial self-supply with water.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] However, it is less common in irrigated agriculture, which is the major water user worldwide.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Water metering is also uncommon for piped drinking water supply in rural areas and small towns, although there are examples of successful metering in rural areas in developing countries, such as in El Salvador.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Metering of water supplied by utilities to residential, commercial and industrial users is common in most developed countries, except for the United Kingdom where only about 52% of users are metered.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In some developing countries metering is very common, such as in Chile where it stands at 96%, while in others it still remains low, such as in Argentina.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Nearly two-thirds of OECD countries meter more than 90% of single-family houses.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] A few are also expanding their metering of apartments (e.g., France and Germany).
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] While the cost of purchasing residential meters is low, the total life cycle costs of metering are high.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] For example, retrofitting flats in large buildings with meters for every flat can involve major and thus costly plumbing work.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Problems associated with metering arise particularly in the case of intermittent supply, which is common in many developing countries.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Sudden changes in pressure can damage meters to the extent that many meters in cities in developing countries are not functional.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Also, some types of meters become less accurate as they age, and under-registering consumption leads to lower revenues if defective meters are not regularly replaced.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Many types of meters also register air flows, which can lead to over-registration of consumption, especially in systems with intermittent supply, when water supply is re-established and the incoming water pushes air through the meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Displacement Water meters do not distinguish between air and water, both are counted as fluid.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] There are two regulations where water companies and meter manufacturers do not comply and charge air for water.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] A measuring system shall be equipped with an effective air/vapor eliminator or other automatic means to prevent the passage of air/vapor through the meter. ref.[Handbook 44 – 2019 3.30.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] S.2.1.] Measuring systems shall incorporate a gas elimination device for the proper elimination of any air or undissolved gases which may be contained in the liquid before it enters the meter.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Water meters are subject to measurement standards and certifications to ensure their accuracy, reliability, and compliance with regulatory requirements.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The most widely recognized standards include the ISO 4064 series and the OIML R49 standards, which define the performance, accuracy classes, and testing procedures for water meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In the European Union, compliance with the Measuring Instruments Directive (MID) is mandatory for water meters sold within member states, ensuring conformity with harmonized European standards.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In the United States, water meters typically adhere to the AWWA (American Water Works Association) C700 series standards, which specify design, materials, and performance criteria.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In Australia and New Zealand, water meters must comply with the AS 3565 standard.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Water meters used in potable water systems are required to meet stringent standards to ensure they do not contaminate the water supply or alter its quality.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] These standards address materials, coatings, and designs that come into contact with drinking water.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In the United States, compliance with NSF/ANSI 61 is mandatory, setting limits on leachable contaminants from water system components.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In Australia and New Zealand, the AS/NZS 4020 standard governs the suitability of products for use with potable water, focusing on factors such as taste, color, and toxicity.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In Latin America, countries like Brazil and Mexico often reference international standards such as those from NSF International.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Water meters are frequently installed in environments where they are exposed to rain, flooding, and dust, necessitating robust protection to maintain accurate and reliable operation.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] An IP68 rating indicates that a device is completely dust-tight and can withstand continuous immersion in water beyond 1 meter depth, as specified by the manufacturer.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Additional sensors integrated into water meters are being explored as part of proof-of-concept (PoC) projects to enhance functionality and provide more detailed insights into water usage and system performance.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] These innovations aim to address challenges such as leak detection, water quality monitoring, and reverse flow detection.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The data collected by the smart meters is analyzed to provide insights into water usage patterns, peak consumption times, and potential issues like leaks or inefficiencies in the system.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Utilities can use this data to optimize water distribution and address problems proactively.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The usage data can be analyzed on device to determine if there is a leak occurring within the building that is being monitored.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The most common leak detection algorithm is to look for 24 hours of constant usage.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] This algorithm works well for residential buildings but has issues with larger commercial buildings where there can be varying levels of constant usage throughout a day without a leak.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] There is disagreement as to the effect of metering and water pricing on water consumption.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The price elasticity of metered water demand varies greatly depending on local conditions.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The effect of volumetric water pricing on consumption tends to be higher if the water bill represents a significant portion of household expenditures.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] There is evidence from the UK that there is an instant drop in consumption of some 10% when meters are installed, although in most instances consumption is not directly measured prior to meter installation, so the benefits are uncertain.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Whilst metered water users in the UK do use less than unmetered users, in most areas metering is not compulsory for homes built before 1990, so the metered customers are to some extent a self-selecting group.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] There is also concern that water metering could be socially regressive, as householders on low incomes are less able to invest in water efficiency measures and may experience water poverty (defined as when a household spends more than 3% of net income on water and sewage services).
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In Hamburg, Germany, domestic water consumption for metered flats (112 liter/capita/day) was 18% lower than for unmetered flats (137 liter/capita/day) in 1992.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Water meter calibration and testing benches employ various methods to evaluate the accuracy and performance of water meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Each method caters to specific testing requirements, such as flow range, precision, or scalability.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Once the water flow is controlled, various measurement methods are employed to assess the performance and accuracy of water meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] A basic and widely used approach where the flow is initiated and stopped over a fixed period or volume.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The meter's reading is compared against a precisely measured reference volume, offering reliable results for low to medium flow rates.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] This method involves collecting the fluid over a known period, typically 60s and measuring its mass using high precision weighing scales.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] This method uses a calibrated reference device, such as a piston prover or master meter, to compare the water volume measured by the test meter.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] It is highly precise and suitable for meters requiring strict compliance with standards.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Continuous flow systems use real-time data acquisition to monitor and compare the meter's readings with those from a calibrated sensor.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] This modern method enables fast and efficient testing, especially for high-volume operations.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Meters can be prepaid or postpaid, depending on the payment method.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] Most mechanical type water meters are of the postpaid type, as are electromagnetic and ultrasonic meters.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] With prepaid water meters, the user purchases and prepays for a given amount of water from a vending station.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The amount of water credited is entered on media such as an IC or RF type card.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] The main difference is whether the card needs contact with the processing part of the prepaid water meter.
[src:mbus-metering/water-metering] In some areas, a prepaid water meter uses a keypad as the interface for inputting the water credit.
